\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid5273668 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did your mother or your father make or mend the family clothes in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Did everything. We had to mend and make do in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would she get the cloth from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh buy it from the - Liskeard, from the local - drapery shops. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did she ever buy clothes new?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, suits of clothes 
we used to buy, but in those days - us youngsters, they could buy a suit of clothes for about - twenty-five, thirty shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How many times would you get new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, a - a suit of clothes would last us probably - four or five years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would your sisters do much dressmaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh yes, they did their bit as well. Yes. They used to - do their own - things you see, and of course mother used to do - some as well. Between 'em they used to - muck in together and keep it going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So by and large you were self sufficient in everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, we had to be self contained.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you ever get clothes second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Jumble sales and - we used to get packmen come around - from as far as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Plymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Yes. There's a firm in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Plymouth{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 now, Costers that used to come around down there, two or three and - and buy - we used to buy from.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 They used to come round every so often did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Every}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
so - about once a month they'd - come around with their packs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about shoes, did you buy shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, buy shoes from - from Liskeard mostly, that's our - home town, about three miles away. From St Kean, about three miles away.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would they be shoes or boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh mostly boots in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember whether your father helped with any of the jobs in the house, help your mother at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well yes, he - he - he did, as mother - wasn't in too good}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 health you see and - he used to - have to do a bit indoors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, cleaning and helping generally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would he do the washing up and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes, that sort of thing, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about decorations and repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well used to have to do it all ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Was this house rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh rented.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 From this chap in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did the landlord very often come down, who was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 He used to come down once a year. Usually. Once a year he used to come - call down, and - usually about a week he
'd spend down - just looking around the countryside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What was he, this chap in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Well when I knew him of course he was a retired gentleman. But - we used to - I think I'm right in saying that - father used to pay about twenty pound a year
 for the rental of the place, that included the foundry, the workshops and the house. Well of course - when you go back to those days - now this place - where I'm - where I've carried on the business for thirty-two years, belonged to Lord Churston of Chur
s
ton Parish Brixham, and the blacksmith who was here before me, he paid ten pound a year rent. Well when I took it - I paid - double the rent, twenty pound a year I paid for this. Five pound for the shops, and fifteen for a house. You see - this is rather 
d
ifferent from any other property, it was an estate place, and the - estate owners - their object was to look after their own tenants, the farming community, and here we had somewhere about - one, two - three, four, five - about six or seven farms, and - a
 blacksmith here had quite enough to do to look after those tenants.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So it was in their interest really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 It was in their interest and that's the reason why - the place was so cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What happened to this Churston?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well about six years
 ago - Lord Churston - sold - the Churston Ferrers estate and the Dean Prior estate, and - in the first instance, Roland Smith the motor magnate bought the both estates. Well he wasn't particularly concerned about the Dean Estate, he was after the Brixham
 
- the Churston Ferrers Estate, because - all that estate was a hundred percent building land, which - since that - has proved to be a money spinner. But the Dean Estate - he sold it again, straight away, and - a - a company of people bought it, known as t
he Devon Investments. Well then they sold it off to the sitting tenants. And at that time of course I bought my property the same as the farmers bought theirs. And I've carried on ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What will happen with your blacksmith's shop and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh - all this now will be demolished for the new dual carriageway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Is there any way to keep it up, set it up somewhere else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well my - two of my employees, one that's been with me for a very long time and one that worked for me private - 
previously - they've gone in partnership, and - they set up down where - used to be the old paper mills, a firm called Reed and Smith owned it years ago, and I can remember when that - in here 1925, they worked that mill from daylight to dark and - night 
s
hift, day and night shift. Yes. Well, the time come I think it was - I won't commit meself, but I got an idea it was just as war finished they - they moved to - I think it was Kilverton, and then they let those premises and - it's been developed into - th
e
re's be three businesses running there for sometime, but it's changed hands from time to time. So one section of this property was available when this had to be demolished, and - my chaps - took it over. And they'll carry on more or less in the same way t
hat I've carried on here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So it's not going to be lost altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh no. It won't be a dead loss. And - the farmers especially, they - they do appreciate it. Because as I say there's no country blacksmith's shop in any of the villages in - in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}South Devon{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember whether your father did any cooking at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh I - I don't think so, no, don't think he would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would he help dress or undress you, bath you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would he ever help to dress or undress you or bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, in - when were was kiddies of course but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh there was no such thing as a - bath in the house in those days, we used to - we used to bath in galvanized baths.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where was that, in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How often a week would you have a bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, we had to - twice - twice a week because it was a smutty job. Especially }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 smiting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 . Forging.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When would you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, every week. Every weekend usually we changed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember whether your father ever read to you or told you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, yes, in our younger days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What sort of stories would he tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well, as a matter of fact father was - a 
great Methodist, he was a - he was a - local preacher for many many years, and - of course he used to spend a - bit of time with us, but in these little country villages most people seemed to - seemed to go for the Church of England, and when - as I - ref
e
rred some time ago, a little while ago, that - when I was about nine or ten year old, I took to go to church blowing the organ. You see, we used to blow the organ like a - forge fire. And I did that up to the time that I - started courting the wife, and I
 
was - seventeen, eighteen, and - I went to - do - used to attend Dolittle church, but - Duloe, Duloe, it's a little village between Liskeard and Looe. Well - incidentally - at St Kean I learnt ringing and I wasn't no more than about - twelve year old when
 
I started ringing, and a - a farmer called Saunders learnt me the way to ring, he was a very old ringer and - we used to get great interest in the ringing, well - when I was courting me wife present wife I attended Duloe church, her father was a gardener 
a
t the Rectory, you see, and these two villages are only a matter of about two miles - not two miles apart, and the vicar, his name at that time - was Barrington Ward, and - Doctor Barrington Ward - I was - well - I suppose - you could say he used to take 
i
nterest in me because the wife's father worked at the rectory, and we used to have - some really good social times, Christmas time we used to go down there and have our Christmas meal, and - really enjoy it. That's how we used to enjoy ourselves in these 
villages, we used to spend a lot of time ringing. And - of course I - more or less attended to that - church until I come to Buckfastleigh. In fact I was married at Duloe church. Yes, I went and - 'cos the wife lived in Duloe village all her like
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you ever a member of the Sunday school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh yes, I used to attend Sunday school. Yes, my father - we had a little chapel at St Kean, a Methodist chapel and - I attended there right up - 'til I - I left the chapel and joined the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you ever a member of a church choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Well no - we - we used to have - some - it is only a small - very small parish church. But - in those days - they all used to attend, the youngsters and the older people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How many times on a Sunday would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh twice a day of course, morning service and evening service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And then you'd go to Sunday school in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And Sunday school in the afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Morning and afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. Service eleven o'clock Sunday mornings, Sund
ay school - for two half past Sunday afternoons, and then the evening service six thirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you go on any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes. In those days - horses and carriages. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Used to go to Looe usual
ly. All the schoolchildren used to go to Looe. For the day. And you used to think you - wonderful job, go down to Looe, a matter of about four miles. Down at the seaside.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And you'd play on the sand and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you play on the sand and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How long would it take, not very long I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh we used to - used to make a day of it, we'd - we'd leave the village - about nine in the morning and get back about - seven - eight 
in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would your parents go with you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes. They used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Quite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
a procession?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember whether your father look after you when your mother went out at all? If your mother had to go out anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh well when we were teenagers you see the three boys were - in the workshops, and the girls naturally, the eldest daughter and the youngest one, they were - indoors home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about when you were still quite small before you started work, did father ever look after you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well he used to pop - to see everything is all right, naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember whether you had any tasks to carry out regularly at home before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, as I say, when - when I was eleven year old I had to work in the work shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Before that were there any things you had to do, apart from the forge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no, not previous to that. Not previous to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You didn't have to chop sticks or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh - 
yes, my word, yes, and - and gardening, good lord I - I used to go and garden when I was only about eight - nine year old, and love it. Used to like the garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So you were really in charge of the garden at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well I was, aye, and the poultry. I looked after the poultry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about your brothers and sisters, would they have anything they had to help with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well, not really, I suppose - I used to do my bit for 'em and then - they more or less had - really speaking more leisure th
an I had, but that - that was our life. Of course they had their hobbies naturally, my eldest brother, he was a great footballer wonderful footballer, he played for Liskeard, he played for Looe, you see, so I mean his time was - more or less occupied.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember whether they helped you, your older brothers, in any way? Did they sort of do things for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, yes, naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things would they help you with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well - quite a lot of things see, they used to - they'd do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would they help you to dress and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes, and - clean boots and all that sort of thing and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were there any other things that you'd do for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes, well - well yes, I - as I say that I used to - when I was old en
ough to - to do the garden and - and - and look after me poultry and one thing and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you ever go errands for your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Beg pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you ever go on errands or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, we used to - we had a l
ittle village - shop in the village, we used to go there for odds and ends. And of course - we used to buy some things at Liskeard. But in those days you could get most things from your little local - country shop. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you expected to go to bed at any certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well yes, when we were youngsters, father was rather strict with us, we used to go to bed early.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How early?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 In fact - in me teenage days - if we weren't in be - at least half past nine, ten o'clock - he'd want to know the reason why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You'd have to be up early as well wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Yes, but - that didn't concern us a bit because - many many nights I've - spent up in me little - meadow in a tent, specially summertime, used to love it, rather sleep up there tha
n I would in - I think the climate in those days was - rather different what it is today. You could sleep in open tent - and really enjoy it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How old were you when you got your tent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh I wasn't very old. Eleven, twelve year old I used to sleep up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you ever a member of anything like the scouts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No. No. I never - I never - joined anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So you weren't a member of any youth organizations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well you see in these little country village you were more or less isol
ated from the towns. Now Liskeard of course they had all these things in - I remember when I was going - I used to walk from St Kean to Liskeard - three miles each way, when I was about attending school, 'course remember I left school when I was eleven ye
a
r old, I had to, and the war went on 'til 1918, well of course - I left - I - I left school at eleven to go to work during the war, and that finished my schooling career, but - previous before I left - I went to Liskeard school, walked there mile, and in 
those days - the lobby doors would be all locked mealtimes. Many times I - when we've had really bad weather I've gone in the lavatory to eat me meal. Used to take sandwiches or pasty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Why would they lock the lobby doors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 They used to look all the school doors, you wasn't allowed inside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Why not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well, they - that was those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When weren't you allowed inside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 During the - out of school hours. Mealtimes, dinnertimes it was closed from - sort of half past twelve to two, and
 summertime - we had a playing field adjoining the school, and - I used to - summertime you could go down there and sit below - oh beautiful in the summer and eat your pasty and - you see, but wintertime when it's really bad weather you'd have to go in un
der somewhere and the only place to go was the lavatory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And they always shut the school completely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Yes, complete, shut the - lobby doors. And I did that - for years, and when my youngest daughter - our youngest - sister started school - I left Liskeard school and went a little place called Twiglen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where's that now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 It's - it's about a - a mile and a half from St Kean, and we used to walk - I used to walk there with her to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 She went to that school did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 She went to that school. Then - then of course when I left to go to work during the war she had to carry on school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 But you stayed at the Liskeard school all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No, no, I left Liskeard and went Twiglen for - might have been -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How do you spell that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Trewrdland, Trewrdland, as you - pronounce it, Trewrdland. That's another typical little country village. Well my father - my father's family - originated from Trewrdland. My father's father was a farm labourer. And I've heard him say that - hi
s money was twelve shillings a week. And grandma - used to have to go out - cutting corn with a pair book in those days. Had to work. And - I had an uncle reared up there - Uncle Jim Carne, eventually he - he was a miller at Stoke Climsland, near Carringt
o
n, and - not many years ago - he did well out there for himself, and - he bought a piece of ground adjoining Trewrdland chapel for a burial ground, because in those days they used to take - take all the corpses to Liskeard to be buried, and believe me - n
o horses used to carry 'em. I've - I've helped carry people to Liskeard from Trewrdland, and if possible they used to arrange the funerals on a Sunday. So everybody could help. And we used to carry 'em to Liskeard - cemetery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of clothes would they wear, was it mourning clothes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh - in those days all black, mourning, everybody mourning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What would happen after, would you have a gathering anywhere after the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Not usually. Because - I mean - families in the country, they
 hadn't got the money to be, see. Perhaps the - the relatives, yes, but not outsiders. Although we - we were all friendly. Now when I used to go on this post round - quite a number of old age pensioners, I used to take their pension to 'em every Friday. Y
o
u see, they couldn't come up to the village post office, some of 'em - so far as two miles to collect their - and we used to do the same thing with gun licences. A farm labourer, even a farmer would say - well - Les, would you get my - gun licence, he'd g
i
ve me his ten shilling note, and - I'd hand it into the post office and - don't matter what they give me but every Friday all the licence money would go in Liskeard and then they were sent out - the Saturday, and I used to take 'em to 'em. That's how we u
sed to carry on. Help each other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When would you do this post round, before you started work in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
d lord yes, quarter to six mornings. And I'd be back about eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Then you'd start work straight away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Then go on to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you have breakfast before or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
I - I'd have breakfast when I come back, just a cup of tea in the morning, and a bit of cake or bun. Do me post round. Come back. And - start to work, and about nine o'clock we'd have our breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things would you have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh nearly always fry. You see, we used to feed our own pigs as I say, we had our own bacon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Who would be there, when you were at St Kean and were still at school, before you start work, who would be there for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, we all family would be there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You'd all be there for breakfast, and what about the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh the same - exactly the same thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You'd all be there then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, all the family, all - all together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things would you eat for the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh, in those days - mother used to - cook everything herself, bake her - own bread, make her - make her own cake and - buns and things. Well you had to, you couldn't buy it in those days like you can now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What time of day would you have the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh usually about half past twelve to one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You say you'd have breakfast about nine o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And nine o'clock breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about when you were going to school, what time would you have breakfast then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh well I had to have breakfast about eight o'clock you see because I had to walk Liskeard, three miles, about an hour, nine o'clock school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would your brothers and sisters have breakfast with you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Because you'd all be going to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 All going to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would your father have breakfast with you then or would he come in at nine o'clock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh nine o'clock he'd have his, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about the evening meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh usually - well more or less any time, when it's convenient. See we used to get home from school, we used to leave school four o'clock, and I'd be home by five. So we'd have our tea about half past five to six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things would you get then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh just ordinary - meal, usually - bread and butter and jam and cake, that was the routine in these days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you have meat or anything at midday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. Oh midday, but - not - tea. Only just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 A cooked meal midday was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Midday cooked meal. And as I say mornings fry - we had our own bacon and - and eggs and - then growing me own potatoes you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh pasties and sandwiches, cheese sandwiches and - whatever was going. But
 of course we wouldn't even have a cup of tea with dinner, just your sandwiches. That's how we used to carry on in those days. There was no such things as school canteens in those days. My word, not likely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you ever remember seeing your mother eating less so that the rest of you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well - I wouldn't suggest that, we were - we always had a - a - a bellyful as they say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You don't remember your father having more than anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no, not a bit. Not a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, we always sit in our own little -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would there be any occasion when you wouldn't eat in the kitchen, when you'd eat in the living room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well very very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When might you, like Christmas Day or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well - for Christmas time perhaps or - if we had any - relatives come, any special - say a birthday party or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You used to have birthday parties did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well yes, in our own little way. Yes. And - I had an aunt 
in Liskeard - she - she was an old maid all her life and she used to take in lodgers, schoolteachers, three of 'em there for years, and - she looked after her grandma, for years, I've got grandma's photograph now, and - we all used to meet in there Christ
m
as time when grandma was alive, but when she passed away - they dwindled away until in the end there was - only just - I used to - look after her, because as a matter of fact - her property was sold eventually - and I bought it for her when I was quite a 
-
 I was no more than about - eighteen and she bought that house for two hundred and seventy five pound. Terrace house, nice house. She - I - I helped to buy it. And - she struggled hard, 'cos I - after I went in - business I wanted her to pay it off. I sai
d
, look auntie, you're paying interest on the - the money that's left, why don't you let me - so - no, you've done your bit, now I'm going to - see it - which she did. And of course when she passed away she left me all her property. And my father, when he 
r
etired down there, he come up here, he was seventy odd then, and - just after - he'd been up here - perhaps six years I suppose, and his sister passed away, and he said, well - and she left me all her property you see, so - he said, what are we going to d
o
 with Annie's? I said, that's - well - why don't you go down there and - and - end the rest of your days, it is your native home, you know everybody there, and there was a gentleman close to him called Harris that he was very friendly with, and they were 
l
ike two brothers, they used to visit each other every day, and eventually Harris passed away, and that finished father. He was eighty-five. And of course then - after he passed away - eventually - I gave the property to me daughter. Incidentally, she sold
 
it to the wife's youngest brother, that's what happened. It's still in the family. Still in the family. In fact he's retiring now, living there. He was a builder by trade and he's made a nice house of it. Well that house today is worth at least four and a
 half to five thousand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you ever have presents and things like that for birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. In our own little way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh, used to buy all sorts of things - of course nothing very expensive you jus
t couldn't afford it. A box of handkerchiefs or toys for the youngsters and so on. Sweets and chocolate, 'cos oh you could buy - you could buy - wonderful packet of chocolates for sixpence in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember any particular birthday at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no, we were all the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You haven't got a particular memory, would you have a party or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well we used to have little - tea parties, same as all families.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Who would you have, would you have friends round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh the - the - friends in the village, the youngsters in the village. More or less our own age.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about Christmas Day, what would you do on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, well naturally we used to have our - turkey or - chicken, whatever we could afford.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you have relatives round then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh - well not normally 'cos all families are home Christmas time. All more or less on their own. But as I say - this doings and the aunt's, we used to go in there Christmas Eve. And - and - have a w
onderful meal, aunt used to - do little things that you wouldn't have - all through the year, such as - various fruits and - so on. That - we really enjoyed it. Used to look forward to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would Christmas Day and Bank Holidays we paid holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
No. In those days you wouldn't - weren't paid - what - what you didn't work. But of course as far as we were concerned in our business as I say - that - and - and - especially latter years, with the depression that we hadn't - hadn't got the money to do i
t with. It was a struggle to - live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about Bank Holidays, were there things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh well, used to have our Bank Holidays of course. But in the vill - in our little village we used to - well have a game of football or - whatever it may 
be, but - personally I used to go out on the farms and help 'em and - or go rabbitting you see. What I used to do with my Bank Holidays. We couldn't afford to go off to the seaside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 I suppose your father would be virtually self employed really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well he was, running his own business. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you have holidays, away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Well - working holidays, you used to work. That's a thing I've never done in all my life, not - when I was home, or even in me own business career - I've - we've never
 been away for an holiday because my wife - she - loves her home, and she wouldn't - she wouldn't - if possible she'd be home in her own - bedrooms to sleep. Now we are getting older we do go down to our daughter weekends. And she's a wonderful daughter. 
I wouldn't be without her for the world. Really marvellous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 She's now in Liskeard is she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh she's really marvellous girl. But of course - we helped them in their young days. And - to be honest when - she married at twenty her husband, he's an ex
ecutive in the telephones now and - and got a good job, but he was a youth in training on the Post Office, and he started courting my daughter - when they were somewhere about - fifteen years of age, but when he was eighteen he had to do his national serv
i
ce, he come back from his national service, and - he was twenty then of course. Well they hadn't been back no more than three months before - the wife said to me - she said - Gwen and Clifford are getting serious you know. So I said, well what about that?
 
She said, well - let's help 'em now while we're alive, not wait 'til we're dead and gone. Well I said - I don't quite agree. I said, they should come up the hard way same as we had to. And mother said, now, don't be like that. Let's help 'em while we'm yo
u
ng, and we - we can afford to do it, so let's do it. And - after a week I said, well all right. I said, but - give Greta to understand this, that - they can't have it twice. If I help 'em now we got our own future to look forward to. So - she said - well 
a
ll right, they want to - get a bungalow or house if they can, and at that time he was working at - Shiphay Repeater Station at Paignton, or Torquay. Shiphay. It's a - it's a - actually near the Torbay hospital, quite close to Torbay hospital, and - he was
 
working there at the home, when he got married. Well - they hadn't been married - well I bought a bungalow for 'em, and then - we furnished it for 'em. And as I say - the money was vastly different what it cost me. I - I - furnished everything on sixty po
u
nd. And it cost me a thousand pound to furnish theirs, I don't suggest we spent it all, but nevertheless - she furnished her place and economically, and she had a bit of money left which she - put away and I told her, I said, now - you've had a good start
, and - just after they got married unfortunately son-in-law contracted TB. He was out to - out to - Bovey Tracey's San}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
 - San}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
torium up - what is the place called? He was out there for - oh over two years. But - and of course we had to help the daughter while he was away, but he come back and fortunately they cured him, made a good job, he was a ver}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 y lucky chap. In fact streptomycin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
 cured - cured him, 'cos in those days they hadn't go no answer to TB. But now they have. They cure 'em in a matter of a short 
time. Well then - I'll give the chap credit, he - he - he don't drink or smoke. He's very fond of sailing. He spends a lot of time sailing, he spends a bit of money on it, but nevertheless he's earning the money now. Well - now they appreciate it. And - t
h
ey can't do enough for us. They can't do enough for us all the time I was in hospital she really - every day never missed, and when her husband was out too off from work, she never missed a single day, all the time he was out there, and the same thing wit
h me, when I was in hospital. I said to her times, well, you don't want to bother to come down every day. Wouldn't think of it. She was there. And of course brought me wife with her. And now -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Start off with your name please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Ernest Lesley Carne my name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And your present address here?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Dean Prior, Buckfastleigh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And you are married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember the year of your marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes - now wait a minute, July - 1929.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember the year of your birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 1903. May the twenty-fourth 1903.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 I was born in a little - country village called Mount, Warlegen Parish, near Bodmin in Cornwall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well I left - I left - Mount, I was only about t
wo years old when I left there - me father at the time was working as a blacksmith - in the - in the - in the mines. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 The tin mines is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes. Then he moved to Moor - a little place called Moors Water, near Liskeard, and - that's where I 
- I was reared up there, and from there, I we went out to - a little village called St Kean, between Liskeard and Looe, and - my father took over a business there that was run be the - well more or less members of the family, my father's sister - married 
a man called Pengelly - in fact was two brothers, and eventually, they finished - retired, and father took in the business, and ran it - right up to - 19 - well in the early '20's, about 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What business was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Agricultural blacksmiths. Count
ry blacksmiths. In those days of course everything was done - more or less with the forge. There was no such thing as - electrical wedding plants, everything was hand forget. And in those days no electric blower things, just - bellows, they used to blow b
y hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How old would you be when you left Bodmin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh when I left Mount I wasn't no more than about two year old, then I went to Moors Water and - when I went to - from there to St Kean I wasn't no more than about - six, seven year old.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So you were in Cornwall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Yes. You see when father - took on the business from the Pengelly's - we were three boys, three sons, I was the youngest, and - father said to us boys when we - got old enough to do anything, and believe me in those days it wasn
't a case of - wait until we left school - at fourteen years of age - I started learning me trade when I wouldn't be - potter about down the blacksmith's shop when I was quite a kiddie, about eight, nine years old, and - as a matter of fact - in 1914 - wh
e
n the war started, we - father employed somewhere about - six or seven staff, and - most of them, bar one one man, the iron moulder that ran the foundry, he was elderly man, but the youngsters were all - young men and most of 'em were in the Territorials.
 
Well when the war broke out of course they had to go. There was only one left, Sidney Harris, I remember him very well, you see, because I was a boy, quite a boy then. And - Sidney - was only one we had left and he said to father one Monday morning - he s
a
id - boss, I shall be leaving Saturday, 'cos in those days - the weekend was Saturday, work from Monday 'til Saturday, and from seven in the mornings 'til half - half past five at night, one o'clock Saturday. That's hours they used to work in those days. 
W
ell - Sidney said, well, I shall be leaving next week boss. So father said, well - what's the trouble Sid? Well, he said, all the rest have gone, I feel that - it's me duty to go. And father said to him, well Sid - you'll regret it you know. So oh well, b
e
ing a young man he felt he should go, well he went. Well he only had a - matter of a month or two training, sent across to France, and he got wounded straight away and ruined his life, and - of course when he come home on leave he said, to father - I wish
 
I'd listened to you now, but it was too late, job's done. Well that meant that we were left with practically nobody in the business, and - I was only eleven year old, and I had to - stay home from school to work. And not eight hours a day. But from daylig
ht 'til dark. And more or less interested and enjoy it. No doubt about that. And - I never regret it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You started off helping your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 I started off helping me father in those days, well, when I was learning me trade, when I got up to - fifte
en, up to twenty, all I had was a shilling a week. That's what father used to give me, a shilling a week, and I used to go Liskeard Saturday nights, I had a friend of mine, he's still living now, he's older than I am, young chap called Coarse, we - in - h
ow it come about, we - we knew each other and we happened to be in a hospital together, and - I went out to that village out - St Neot}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 s village, it's close to Mount where I was born. Beg pardon? St Neot. It's - St Neot, Wargegin, it's Warlegin Parish, but 
St Neot is a little small village, and Mount is a little small village, but it's all in the same district, and it comes now in the Bodmin area you see. So - Jack Coarse and I were - in hospital together, and naturally chatting away well while in were in t
h
ere. And when we come out of hospital I went out to - St Neot to a ringing test, well in Cornwall we - especially in the country that's all we had to do, I used to spend a lot of time ringing. Ringing. Bell ringing. And at St Kean I - I - below the organ 
a
t the church, that was in the days - no electricity, used to pump the organ like the forge bellows, and - well I wasn't no more than about nine year old when I started to blow the organ at the parish church, and I carried on what - 'til - when I started -
 
started courting the wife in the next village. Then I gave it up then because I used to attend that church you see, so we used to spend a lot of time ringing, and - eventually, in our little village we - the little parish hall close to the church - the vi
c
ar did it, he opened it up and got a little billiard table, half size billiard table and we used to spend quite a lot of our evenings there playing billiards. Well I was very fond of billiards and Jack, this Jack Coarse I'm talking about, he was a really 
good billiard player. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Is he about the same age as you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh he's a bit older than I am. In fact - incidentally a little while ago I was in Cornwall on business - and I made it me business to call and see him, and - we had quite a chat. And I
 hadn't seen him for - over fifty years. 'Cos I've been up here since 1925, you see, we've been out of touch. But I called and see him the other day, and - our Jack and I - we - after we come in hospital, it is only over to going to a ringing festival, al
w
ays have it Easter Monday. There's about twenty parishes meet at this - one particular village and have a ringing festival. And - of course - it's only about ten minutes you're ringing, well then you've got practically all the day to yourself, and Jack sa
i
d to me, he said - you can play billiards Les. So - oh, I said, yes, I - can play billiards, I said, we've only got a half sized table. Oh, he said - cos he was really - mad about billiards. So he said, come down the village hall, and believe me in that l
i
ttle village they had two full size tables. And he said to me, well we'll have a game of billiards. Well we had a game of billiards. And - the first game I beat him. And he said to me, where did you learn your billiards? So I said, only home in our own li
t
tle village place. Oh, he said, I can see we'm going to have a jolly good time. Well believe me for years - we used to meet in Liskeard Saturday evenings, I used to have to walk three miles to Liskeard, get in there about half past six. Jack and I would g
o
 in the Liberal club, I was a member of the Liberal club, have a game of billiards, tuppence. Then he was a member of Conservative club. Went in Conservative club and had a game of billiards tuppence. Come out from there about half past eight to nine, go 
in the fish and chip shop, and have a really good feed for sixpence. Ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
pence - of a Saturday night, and really enjoyed ourselves, and we did that for years. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How far away is St Kean from Mount?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Somewhere about - nine miles I should say, eight or nine miles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How old were your brothers, were they much older than you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
My - eldest brother, he's at South Moultus now, yes, he's - he's somewhere about five years older than I am, somewhere about seventy-five or six - seventy-five or s
ix. And me second brother, he's in Africa, he's been to Africa since - he went to Africa in the early twenties, in those days things were pretty grim. Now, to give you an idea - with a farming community. I was always - interested in cattle, and when I was
 
quite a youngster I used to feed a few pigs, more or less as an hobby. Well of course the incentive of making a bit out of it. Well in those days - I could buy a barley meal for five shillings a hundredweight, and I used to do a post round in our little v
illage, for about two hours a morning, my money in the Post Office was seven and sixpence a week. Seven and sixpence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Was that when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
eg your pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you still at school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. Just - some time
 after I left school, well I should say I was - well, about fifteen, and - I used to help the farmers with their harvest, you see, and they used to - they - never paid me much in money but - meal, and - turnips or straw, whatever I wanted, and they paid m
e
 - paid me well for it. But coming back to the - to the value of farming. I could buy barley meal - for five shillings an hundredweight. Best molasses for six shillings a hundredweight. Well that's seven and sixpence a week I used to earn with me post rou
nd, 'cos my father only give me a shilling a week pocket money when we was learning our trade. And I used to buy a hundredweight of meal a week which cost me five shillings. You see?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Whose pigs were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh - my pigs, I - I - I did it myself, an
d as I say farmers used to help me as well because they used to give me bags of meal and - that's, how I used to carry on. And - but when it come to the early twenties things were so grim - now - I've bought pigs in Liskeard market }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 wieners}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791  seven weeks old 
for half a crown a piece. Two and sixpence each. I've seen fat bullocks sold in Liskeard market for fifteen pound a piece. Well a little while ago I had some customers in my shop discussing - present day prices - with early twenty prices. And there was on
e or two there my age, and when I referred to this - one farmer said to me, he said - oh ge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
s perfectly, but, he said, you talk about fat bullocks fifteen pound a piece, he said, I've seen 'em sold for twelve pound a piece, and - and sheep, fat sheep a poun
d a piece, that's what it was like in the early twenties. Well the time come - that - we just couldn't live home there, and eventually - I come to Buckfastleigh, and worked for - a firm called Wilcox, an iron foundry, and they had a really - nice little -
 
foundry and we used to make casts standing up to five, six ton weight. And - my money in those days was one and a penny an hour. Which meant that - which meant that - the time they take the insurance money out I used to bring home about two guineas a week
. And - and that's all I earned up to 1937.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were your parents still in Cornwall then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Me parents were still in Cornwall, in fact my father, he ran a business for a - for a country blacksmiths shop, he used to manufacture things like I've done he
re, I've carried on much the same way as he did. In fact we - we - we still make these things hand made. And there's a great demand for it, because - everything today is mass produced, and believe me, you can't compare it with hand produced goods.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you married when you came over to Buckfastleigh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No, I come to Buckfastleigh 1925, and I - I was here four years, I married in 1929. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Your wife was a Cornish girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 She come from - near St Kean, a little place called Duloe, betwe
en Liskeard and Looe. And - well I was - what was I, twenty-seven or eight when I got married and well of course we couldn't marry afore, we hadn't got the money. And when I married - everything - including the expenses and the furniture which we bought s
econd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 hand, I spent sixty pound. And what - what do you want today. Two or three thousand to furnish let alone -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Sixty pound would be quite a bit in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 In those days admitted. Oh I'm sorry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember why your father made the initial moves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Yes, because of the depression. We had a fantastic depression in those days. And as I referred just now - the price of cattle which meant - that the farmers hadn't got money to buy - buy new -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When I was born? Oh now you've asked me rather a complicated question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 In his twenties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
See, I was the youngest boy. And - oh he was a bit older than that because - when he left Mount - from the mines, blacksmith - he went down to Mo
ors Water, I was only about two year old when I left Mount, and he worked for the Liskeard and Looe Railway Company, that was long before the great Western took over that line. You see, it was a private company, like most branch lines. Well - not only - d
i
d he work with the railway company but he had a little small blacksmiths shop there and that's how he started his career. You see? And from there he - as I say, he moved to St Kean, where he took over from the Pengelly's, to carry on their business, which
 he did right up to the early twenties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where did he come from originally, was it Mount originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh Liskeard. The Carn'es are a very old Cornish family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How about your mother, where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 The same thing applied, she was a Liskeard person.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Now how old would she be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 She's about the same age as father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So you'd say they were about thirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Probably so - I'm afraid I can't - go back quite as far as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So your father sort of did blacksmith work and all that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, country blacksmith. Country blacksmith. He used to shoe horses, and - lay plough cutters in they days which now }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 today it's all steel discs on p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 loughs, but there's no - craftsmanship in - repairing - in fact no 
craftsmanship in repairing any machinery. It's all parts and - just assembled, but in those days as I said a lot of things had to be made with the forge, all hand made with the forge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember if he ever did anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well - no, all 
blacksmithing. And - of course - we had - we had fitting shops and we had our own foundry. Now - when I started to learn the trade father said to us boys - now - learn whatever trade you wish. But take my tip, and have a little bit of each of it. You'd ne
v
er know what you want in life. Now - when I went in business I appreciated it because I could use the forge - well almost as well as me father did. And - but I was always keen on foundry work, and when our old moulder passed away I wasn't no more than abo
ut fifteen, and I had to take charge of the foundry, and I ran that foundry up to the time it closed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When did it close?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well it closed in - about 1920 after the war, the first world war, when the - that was when the depression started from the t
wenties up to the thirties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh no. No. We - we existed. We existed. But - if you compare it with the present day conditions it's vastly different. You see in those days our - well our moulder
 was - he was called Harry Davies, I always remember him, I learnt me trade with him. In our own foundry. That's how I learnt me trade with him, and - his money in those days was somewhere about - thirty shillings a week. Tradesman in those days. But of c
ourse - things were - the cost of everything was vastly different, and - and people seemed to be happy, we used to enjoy ourselves. We used to enjoy ourselves. Oh - I've got a friend coming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did your mother have any jobs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No. In fact mother didn't enjoy too good a health and - well - we were five children so she had quite enough to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 There were five of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Five of us. Three boys and two girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How old were the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Me eldest sister, she's - she'd the second, s
he's somewhere about seventy-three. And - me youngest sister, she was born after me, she's the youngest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember whether she ever had any job before she got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Your mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No. Never. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 We'll talk about life at home at St Kean because that's probably the one you remember most?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes. That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How many rooms were there in that house at St Kean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh we had - three bedrooms. It was a fairly big house, it's a - the property actually - be
longed to a man called Dawe in Glasgow, I always remember him. And - the Pengelly's - rented it under Mr Dawe for many years. Well of course when - Uncle John Pengelly - was - closing up the business and he told Dawe that father was interested which was i
n the family - 'cos uncle John married father's sister, so - it was quite simple really, Dawe turned it round to father you see, and he carried on, until the time come that - we had to close it up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 This is when you were living in Mount?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No, we were living at St Kean, when it closed up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 But you moved to St Kean because this property became available?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
That's right, yes. You see, father moved from Mount to Moors Water when he worked for the Liskeard Railway, and he had this little small b
lacksmith's shop, well when the Pengelly's got on in years and they decided to pack up - father - naturally through the family - was attached and he took it on. But of course we were young boys then and - his idea was that for future for us you see. Which
 
of course - up to a point was, we learnt our trades home. And - we were capable then of - of going out and getting our own living. But - it was impossible to think of carrying on business. But - personally I always had that - incentive, that - I should - 
keep the business going if possible, and - there's medals that my father won - going back to 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 For forging and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 For - for - implements he invented. Yes. Silver and bronze medals. And in 1916 - I showed it the - the Cornwall Country sho
w at Liskeard being me native home town, and I had a wonderful time there. And - I won two medals there, a silver and a bronze, for me own inventions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Was your business at Dart Mills or here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No, I've - I've - actually turned the business over t
o - one chap been with me ever since he left school. And of course I had no sons, so I've more or less looked on him same own son, and - I tried to see him right, which he's started off - on a really good footing. And there's no reason why he shouldn't ca
r
ry on quite satisfactory because he's been brought up my way, and - all my customers here appreciate it, for the simple reason that old country smiths are dying out. I could reckon up - village after village here in South Devon - where there used to be a 
blacksmith, now there's none whatever. And - I think I'm safe in saying that we're about the only one's that carry on in the same tradition as the old country blacksmith - anywhere in South Devon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things do you make?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well we - we 
make harrows - similar what my father made - well going back - sixty, seventy, eighty years ago. Which are practical - made things. And of course now in - modern times we've had to adapt ourself to some of the modern idea, but even then we still forge som
e of the work - which is - farm more efficient than the - mass produced - machinery.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So you reckon the biggest custom would be farming people still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, it's practically all agriculture. We do - we do quite a lot of - work for the councils,
 Devon Country Council, Oxley Urban District Council, Ashburton - Urban District Council, Totnes Rural Council, do quite a lot - work for 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you always do the same thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, they did the same thing. They did the same thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did they set up their own businesses as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No. No. I was the only one that - carried on in father's - way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did anyone besides your parents and your brothers and sisters live in the house at St Kean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You didn't have any relatives or lodgers living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No relatives, no lodgers, just our own family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How many rooms would there be downstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well there was a kitchen, and - one big sitting room and a small sitting room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would you have your meals, in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh in the kitchen the meals of course. Of course in those days you see all the cooking was done with - coal stoves. That's a thing that we used to make. In our foundry. We used to make coal castings and - make the stoves, make - hundr
eds of 'em in our time. Until of course when I - when the gas cookers - come into being. And - and that wasn't 'til - way on 19 - 20's to 30's. Because - when I come to Buckfastleigh and worked in the foundry, that's what I did for a very long time, that 
w
as at the time - when they started building council houses here extensively, in fact - there was one batch of houses built out to Buckfast before I come there, but the stoves then were Wilcox's stoves. And very popular because it was locally made. And - a
n
d in those days very efficient. The cooking of a coal stove - is far more superior than the present day - methods. More wholesome altogether. And - when I come here - they started building the - the first lot of council houses in Buckfastleight, and - now
 they've put up - quite a number. But - as I say - the stoves in those days were home made by our local foundries. And we did the same thing - where I come from at St Kean's, we had our own little foundry and we used to make all our own castings.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would the foundry be, would it be in the back yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no, adjoining the blacksmiths shop and fitting shops and - all - all in one block.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So it would be quite a big complex really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Quite a big - quite a - quite a - quite a - big place there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you have a garden or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh yes, we had - vegetable garden and - a - that's a thing that - I used to do most of the gardening, I used to love my gardening. Well as I say, it's all attached to agriculture, and - I
 used to go out as I told you just now, and help farmers quite a bit with the harvest, and they used to appreciate and they used to pay me well in goods.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would you keep the pigs, would they be in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well I had a meadow there about two acres that I used to - and I had a piggery, a little piggery - where I used to feed me pigs.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of things would you grow in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh, all vegetables. Potatoes, beans, green}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 stuff. Practically everything we needed for the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So you wouldn't have to buy much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. We didn't - we couldn't buy anything. We hadn't - we - hadn't got the - we had to grow it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about things like hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh fowls, I used to keep fowls. Oh yes, I used to keep - I used to keep
 - well besides this - two acres I had I had another little meadow belonging to the - blacksmiths shops which I rented, and - I used to keep - well - anything up to - fifty, sixty hens and supply all our family with eggs. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you ever eat the hens as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Beg your pardon?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you eat the hens as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. We used to feed the cockerels, we used to - used to feed the cockerels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you get meat from outside as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, yes - well just what - mother could afford to buy. And the butcher used to come to our place Mondays and Fridays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How often would you have meat do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well - usually - once a week. And then - poultry when we wanted it. When we wanted a change we'd -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you eat the pigs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh we used to have - yes, I used to - used to salt in me own pigs in those days. Yes, always feed a pig for ourselves. And of course in those days we used to feed 'em up to about ten or twelve score, and - and a pig that weight would 
last a family about twelve months. We used to salt 'em in in the - in the - what we used to call pig trundles, big oak wood trundles, salt 'em in of course it would keep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You wouldn't have deep freeze or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no, there wasn't such a thing in those days, my word.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about things like tinned meat or dried vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
No, there wasn't such a thing in those days. No, my word, no such thing. Absolutely out of the question. We had to be - really speaking more or less self supporting. And produce all we could possibly pr - produce to - to - to live, to pay our way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember if your mother or father ever made their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Made their own what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Especially when we were o
ut at Mount because all women in those days used to - bake their own bread. And believe me - far superior to what you could buy - at the bakers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What about things like bottled jam and fruits?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes. And make her own jam. Yes? I've been out many a
 time pick blackberries. And of course we'd get apples from farmers, blackberry and apple jam. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you grow any fruit in the garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. We had no fruit trees. No fruit trees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you go mushrooming or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No, but we us
ed to get mushrooms from on the farms you know. We used to go out picking mushrooms. Yes. And - I used to go out catching rabbits. Yes, many a time. In fact -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What time of day would you have to go out to get rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, used to go out usua
lly - Saturday afternoons, you see, during the week we were working from daylight 'til dark. And - usually Saturday afternoons I used to go catch rabbits. And always allowed ee - well average two or three rabbits a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would you stew them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh, all ways, you could stew a rabbit, you could - roast a rabbit. Rabbit pie. Heaps of ways of cooking rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Didn't the farmers mind you taking them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No, because I used to help 'em with their harvest, I had the privilege of - catching rabbits. 
That's how we used to live. In fact - believe me, I did exactly the same thing when I come to Buckfastleigh in the - 1925 - it's only natural there was - there's - some farmers in the area that come from Cornwall, that's how I knew 'em, and the same thing
 applied, I used to go and help 'em with their harvest and used to - do a few little jobs for 'em, and - naturally they used to look after me with - apples and fruit and I could catch as many rabbits as I want.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would you live when you first came to Buckfastleigh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh in a little cottage adjoining Wilcox's foundry. Down in the centre of Buckfastleigh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What happened to Wilcox's foundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well eventually - eventually - many years ago now he had to close it because - wages were increasi
ng fast. That - the owner told me himself since I've been in business I - I asked }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15340754\charrsid11994791 him one day - we were always pal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
ly, after - years after I left him, and I owned this land down by the station, we used to meet there and have a chat, and I said to him one - 
when the foundry closed I said, oh - what - what's the reason you closed the foundry? He said, to be honest, he said, I can buy me castings cheaper than I can get 'em made. That's what he told me. Cheaper than I can make 'em. And that's the reason they cl
osed it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember whether your mother ever paid anyone to help her in the house at St Kean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
No, because in - country villages - you'd get willing helpers if - in fact my - mother unfortunately, she - didn't enjoy very good health. And - 
the local women in the village used to come in and help. And of course fortunately the elder sister was always home so - right up to the time she married. But - in those days - in country villages one would help the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 So it was more a sort of neighbourly thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Neighbourly, absolutely. But we don't get that sort of thing these days. We - admitted - here in Dean we're very fortunate, we've got some good friends. We've got some really good friends here, and - my next door neighbours, we've - w
e were - living together for a long long time and we saw the last of 'em, now they're - their generation of children, especially one of the daughters, she comes in with my wife practically every day and has a cup of tea together, so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 She's round there now actually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Beg your pardon? Yes, well Mrs Watts - see my - my wife unfortunately, she's not enjoying too good health lately, and - Mrs Watts comes down - and - give us an hand, she does all the cleaning. She's - she's very good indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 This is like a tradition really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 It - it's a tradition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you do the washing at home or have it sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh - oh no, we had to do all our own washing in those days. They used to wash -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 To go back to when you were at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Can you remember whether you were allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh well, yes, because - all the school - children that - had their meals at school used to used just get together and have our sandwiches and pasties, whatever we had.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 At home though could you talk at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Beg your pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When you were at home, when you were having breakfast and things like that, could you talk then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well - we were disciplined. Yes. Just normal things, but if you - if you - had too mu
ch - gab as father used to call it - he'd say now, that's enough. Get on with your meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When you wanted something like the salt would you have to ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no. Yes, please can I have this or please can I have that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Do you remember whether grace was said at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You'd have things like family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit up in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well I don't suggest that they were - fussy that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What would be your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well they'd want to know the reason why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 That didn't happen very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. No, we were hardy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you allowed to cho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745875\charrsid11994791 ose}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791  what you wanted to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no. Oh no. You had to eat - what was prepared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Could you bring a book or toys to the table?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 No. Not mealtimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 W
ell when you'd finished. Just say, please dad, can I - leave. You see? I don't suggest that applied when we got older but when we were youngsters fair enough. We had to use our manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you have the same position at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. Always had our own places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would your father be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh at head of the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did he do the carving and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 He - he did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How was the meal served, would your mother serve it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Was there any special order she served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh no, just ordinary routine. She knew just what - she - oh she'd do it on the table you see, all the - vegetables and things were on the - top of the stove, and she'd take it off on the table, father would cut the meat, and put on plates
 down and she would put the vegetables and just hand it out to you. Each of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were you the youngest of all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 I was the youngest boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 But you had a younger sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Younger sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Where would you sit before you were old enough to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Well in the little kitchen we had there was a sort of recess. And - I used to sit in this corner. And me - two brothers - next to me and the two girls on the other side of the table, mother up one end of the table and father at the head.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did that apply to your little sister as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. With me elder sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Who would help feed you before you were old enough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well mother of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Who would put you to bed in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh mother. Yes. 'Til we were old enough to care for ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What were the arrangements, you say you had three bedrooms, would the boys be in one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 The boys in one bedroom, the girls in another and the parents in another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, quite free.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You found she was quite affectionate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 If you had any worries could you share them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes. We had to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh - the same, but unfortunately he enjoyed very good he
alth. Right through life, same as I have. In fact I don't think he ever had in - actually illness, he had one or two accidents but - no serious illness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What would happen when your mother was ill, would the neighbours come in to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh yes, we
ll to be honest she used to - she used to get epileptic fits. And - unfortunately she ended up practically - like all cases - nine out of ten the same. What happened in the end, her - I've tried to forget it for many years but - since I've been to Buckfas
t
leigh, she - in those days in the front room used to have open grate you see, in fact this grate father made himself, a rather big grate, she had a huge fire in, and he was out on a job, with a firm that he was running for, and - they was out on a job and
 
when they come home one evening, he come in the kitchen and she'd - fallen in the fire, her face - and she lost - about - all one side of her face right away, and - of course they phoned me up, I went home, and - well she lived about - a fortnight. But - 
all th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745875\charrsid11994791 ey could do was - inject morphine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791  to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Were they still in Cornwall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 This was in Cornwall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 You were working for Wilcox's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 That's when I was working for the Wilcox's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 How do you think your parents expected you to behave towards them in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh well, we - as I say, we were disciplined. And - we had to tow the line. Well father was very very strict, right up to the time that - I - more or less up to the time I married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Would he punish you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well, now, I don't say he would strike us for anything but he would give us a really good talking to. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 He didn't use a stick or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh no. Not - no, no, none of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well they expected us - to grow up in the same - same as they were you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of values did you think they wanted you to have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 The what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What kind of values?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Well the same as them of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Which is what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Well - we - we were brought up to be truthful and honest, and - father used to drive it into us. All through life. And I found the same thing in business, and that's the reason I've done so well. You've got to - be honest with people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 And friendly with people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh definitely, now believe me - since January - and since I've been home from hospital I've had quite a number of customers been in to see me, and - I said, now, I'll give you - our new phone number if you want any busine
ss done contact these boys, and I said, I've brought 'em up my way and there's no reason why you shouldn't be treated the same as I've tried to do, and quite a number have said now, if I want anything I shall be contacting you, which is natural. Because I
 still more or less got an interest in them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 It really is a family concern?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 It's a family - tradition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What did your parents think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Think of what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Swearing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh they wouldn't have that no price. They wouldn't have
 - of course you appreciate the times are vastly different now what they used to be. My father was - very very strict, especially - he was a very strong teetotaller and never touched anything in his life, well - unless of course it was sickness, and then 
h
e was very reluctant, because I've been home before now when he's been poorly and I said, now look, you drink this, perhaps a drop of whisky or a drop of brandy. Well he - he - he'd be very very adamant to touching it, but - I used to tell him, I said - i
t's a medicine and you've got to take it, you see. But as far as - I was concerned personally, if he saw me - drinking anything alcoholic, my word he - he would go for me. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Even when you were old enough to go to pubs and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Yes
. I mean times are vastly different in business, now that's one thing I never done in all me life. I like a glass of beer as well as the next, but that's a thing I never done in me life, is touched anything - during the day. Lat thing at night, yes, of co
u
rse if a customer come in and say, well come - come down with me and have a drink, I'd go willingly, but I've had travellers come in here all these thirty-two years, they do their business, say - well I've got - quarter hour to spare, come and have a drin
k? No thank you. That's a thing I never do. Touch anything by day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did you have anything like a temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh well no, of course father was a great temperance man and - he brought us all up in the same way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did they actually have an organization?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Because my wife's father was the same. He was very very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Did they have any sort of temperance organization?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 Oh they did in their time. They did in their time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5273668 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 What would happen when grown ups were talking, we you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16138623 EC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
Oh yes. Oh yes, when you got older of course. You see, the time comes when any person - they - they - they get to feel, well I'm capable of looking after meself. Now that's the only time I think I ever had - a word about it with fa
ther when I was courting my wife - present wife, my eldest sister was courting a farmer, farmer's son, and he used to come home naturally, and he'd stay perhaps 'til midnight. I always remember it, when I was courting me wife and I used to go to do the ri
