ging you see, and - one night I come home and I wasn't much after ten, next morning - at breakfast table - father would look - look at ee really grim, and - he said to me, where was you to so late last night? And I said, why, I was old enough then to look
 
after myself, I was about eighteen. He said, where was you to so late last night? So I said, why? Well, he said, your place is home here by ten o'clock. I said, look, as long as Albert - Craigie can come here and stop 'til midnight I shall please myself w
hat time I come in. I said, I'm quite capable now of looking after meself. Never said a word after. Well that's - that's how we carried on. Never said a word after.
