 to part. And of course naturally we'd been going - ever so long, she said - all right, I'll go with you. Now I said, look, we've got nothing to chance no more than me, it's both our own responsibility, but I said, I've been offered a job black on white, 
l
ong as the present boss is in - so long as the firm goes on, so I said, well - we've got at future. And she said, it's all right, I've made up me mind, I'm going. Right. So her said, in the morning I'll tell mother. Well of course I had to leave down ther
e
 about six o'clock to catch the seven o'clock ferry Torpoint. And - I left, come back. And when mother come down - Bess she's called, she said - mother I'm getting married. Her mother said - that's the finest thing you can do. Her said, you'll be all righ
t
 you don't want to worry, he'll look after ee. So her said, well, he told me straight that if I don't get married he won't come home any more. She said, now that's the honest thing you can do. So she said, well look, you know what father's like, you'd bet
