Oh, quite all right. But - it was her leaving home. See? And - what happened was - it wasn't long after the poor old chap died pretty well sudden, he was only ill for a few days. We
ll then mother - me youngest brother - got married, and unfortunately - within two years he lost his wife with TB. And of course mother was getting older. Mother was seventy. So - and my wife's health broke up, and I - I - I've - I found out in the end, t
u
mbled to it what the trouble, she was worrying about her mother. And - I was down Dale - foundry outside our cottage one evening washing, and our neighbours, good neighbours we had down there, wonderful neighbours, and Mrs Lee - come over, always used to 
c
ome over evening for half hour, and I said to Mrs Lee, I said, here I - I - I've tumbled to the trouble, or tumbled to - what's wrong with my - missus. I said, hers worrying her mother. That's what it is. So well ee know what to do don't ee? Tell her to g
e
t her mother off with her, and - she mentioned it, she said - Bessie, I know what your trouble is, worrying about your mother. So her said, get your mother up here with you. So her said, oh I can't manage here with mother, we've only got the two bedrooms.
 
Her said, now you can manage. Gret was a baby then of course, a young kiddie growing up, she said, now - you can manage, 'cos you've room for a bed - single bed for Greta in - in your mother's room and - you and your husband got your own room, and that's 
what we did, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7745875\charrsid11994791 we brought up, well mother lik}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14307531\charrsid11994791 
ed - twelve years after that. And - and my wife - her health improved immediately. So - that was all right. But that was the position parents in those days. See, she'd been home all her life, they didn't want her to leave.
